EXPERIMENT 2: RESIZE AND SACALING OF IMAGE(aug 2023)¶

#1. Image resizing refers to the scaling of images. Scaling comes in handy in many image processing as well as machine learning applications. It helps in reducing the number of pixels from an image and that has several advantages e.g. It can reduce the time of training. It also helps in zooming in images. Many times we need to resize the image i.e. either shrink it or scale up to meet the size requirements. OpenCV provides us several interpolation methods for resizing an image. Choice of Interpolation Method for Resizing: cv2.INTER_AREA: This is used when we need to shrink an image. cv2.INTER_CUBIC: This is slow but more efficient. cv2.INTER_LINEAR: This is primarily used when zooming is required. This is the default interpolation technique in OpenCV.

SYNTAX: -cv2.resize(src, dsize[, dst[, fx[, fy[, interpolation]]]])¶

 src: -source/input image
 dsize: -desired size for the output image
 fx: -scale factor along the horizontal axis
 fy: -scale factor along the vertical axis

Resize the image changing only Height¶

import cv2 as cv img=cv.imread("Downloads\color.jpeg") print("original image:",img.shape)

using opencv¶

cv.calcHist() function can be used to compute image histograms.

SYNTAX: -calcHist(sourceimage, channels, mask, histSize, ranges ) Where 1)images: source image of type uint8 or float32. it should be given in as a list, ie, [gray_img]. 2)channels: it is also given in as a list []. It the index of channel for which we calculate histogram. 3)mask: mask image. To find histogram of full image, it is set as None. 4)histSize: this represents our BIN count. 5)ranges: Normally, it is [0,256]. enumerate() allows us to iterate through a sequence cv.equalizeHist() Histogram equalization improves the contrast of an image, in order to stretch out the intensty range. SYNTAX: -equalizeHist(Source Matrix, Destination Matrix)

from matplotlib import pyplot as plt

##function return a copy of the array collapsed into one dimension.
hist,bins=np.histogram(image.flatten(),256,[0,256])
## want to compute the cumulative sum of array elements over a given axis.
line=hist.cumsum()
line_normalized=line*float(hist.max())/line.max()
plt.plot(line_normalized,color="b")
plt.hist(image.flatten(),256,[0,256],color='r')
##used to get or set the x-limits of the current axes.

plt.legend(('line','histogram'),loc= "upper left") ## an area describing the elements of the graph

EDGE DETECTION OF AN IMAGE¶

Edge detection is a technique of image processing used to identify points in a digital image with discontinuities, simply to say, sharp changes in the image brightness. These points where the image brightness varies sharply are called the edges of the image

sobel method(Aug 2023)¶

The Sobel filter is used for edge detection. It works by calculating the gradient of image intensity at each pixel within the image SYNTAX: -Sobel(src, dst, ddepth, dx, dy)

In [ ]:
import cv2
import numpy as np
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
#loading image
img = cv2.imread("C:\\Users\\91938\\OneDrive\\Desktop\\chandrayaan\\moon1.jpeg")
#converting to grayscale
gray = cv2.cvtColor(img , cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
#remove noise
img = cv2.GaussianBlur(gray,(3,3),0)
#convolute with proper kernels
sobelx = cv2.Sobel(img, cv2.CV_64F,1,0,ksize=7) #x
sobely = cv2.Sobel(img, cv2.CV_64F,0,1,ksize=7) #y
plt.subplot (2,2,1),plt.imshow(img, cmap = 'gray')
plt.title('Original'), plt.xticks([]), plt.yticks([])
plt.subplot(2,2,3), plt.imshow(sobelx, cmap = 'gray') 
plt.title('Sobel X'), plt.xticks([]), plt.yticks([])
plt.subplot(2,2,4),plt.imshow(sobely, cmap = 'gray')
plt.title('Sobel Y'), plt.xticks([]), plt.yticks ([])
plt.show()

morphological operations(Aug 2023)¶

Types of Morphological operations

1.Erosion: Erosion removes pixels on object boundaries.¶

2.Dilation: Dilation adds pixels on the object boundaries. 3.Opening: The opening operation erodes an image and then dilates the eroded image, using the same structuring element for both operations. 4.Closing: The closing operation dilates an image and then erodes the dilated image, using the same structuring element for both operations.

# 1.Morphological transformations are some simple operations based on the image shape.It is normally performed on the binary images.(Binary images are images whose pixels have only two possible intensity values. They are normally displayed as black and white.Numerically, the two values are either 0 for black or either 1 or 255 for white.) 2.It needs two inputs, one is our original image, second is called structuring element or kernel which decides the nature of operations. 3.Two basic morphological operators are Erosion and Dilation. Then its variant forms like opening, closing, Gradiant etc. also comes into play.

DIALATION(represented by the symbol ⊕)¶

expand the boundary¶

noise remover¶

Dilation adds pixels on the object boundaries. The assigned structuring element is used for probing and expanding the shapes contained in the input image. In Specific, it acts like local maximum filter. Dilation has the opposite effect to erosion . It adds a layer of pixels to both the inner and outer boundaries of regions. SYNTAX: -cv2.dilate(src, dst, kernel)

opening(A o B=(A⊖B)⊕B)¶

background noises will remove¶

The opening operation erodes an image and then dilates the eroded image, using the same structuring element for both operations. It is achieved by first eroding an image and then dilating it. Opening removes any narrow connections and lines between two regions.The opening operation erodes an image and then dilates the eroded image, using the same structuring element for both operations. Morphological opening is useful for removing small objects from an image while preserving the shape and size of larger objects in the image. Syntax: cv2.morphologyEx(image, cv2.MORPH_OPEN, kernel)

closing(A • B=(A⊕B)⊖B)¶

reverse of opening¶

dlation followed by erosion¶

The closing operation dilates an image and then erodes the dilated image, using the same structuring element for both operations. It is done by first dilating the image and then eroding it. The order is the reverse of opening. Closing fills up any narrow black regions or holes in the image.The closing operation dilates an image and then erodes the dilated image, using the same structuring element for both operations. Morphological closing is useful for filling small holes from an image while preserving the shape and size of the objects in the image. Syntax: cv2.morphologyEx(image, cv2.MORPH_CLOSE, kernel)

morphological gradient¶

it gives outline of an image¶

morphological gradient is the difference between the dilation and the erosion of a given image. The morphological gradient highlights sharp gray-level transitions in the input image. The difference between the dilation and the erosion of the image. This is used to find boundaries or edges in an image. It recommended to apply some filtering before calculating the gradient because it is very sensitive to noise. Syntax: cv2.morphologyEx(image, cv2.MORPH_GRADIENT, kernel)

blackhat¶

Black hat transform highlight all the object in white on a black background. The difference between the closing of an image and the input image itself. This highlights the narrow black regions in the image. The bottom hat transform closes an image, then subtracts the original image form the closed image. The bottom hat transform can be used to find intensity troughs in a grayscale image.

Image segmentation( Aug 2023)¶

Thershold method¶

#cv2.threshold(source,thresholdValue,maxval,thresholding techinique) This is perhaps the most basic and yet powerful technique to identify the required objects in an image. Based on the intensity, the pixels in an image get divided by comparing the pixel’s intensity with a threshold value. The threshold method proves to be advantageous when the objects in the image in question are assumed to be having more intensity than the background (and unwanted components) of the image. At its simpler level, the threshold value T is considered to be a constant. But that approach may be futile considering the amount of noise (unwanted information) that the image contains. So, we can either keep it constant or change it dynamically based on the image properties and thus obtain better results. Based on that, thresholding is of the following types:

Three types of Thresholding techniques¶

In [ ]:
Classified into 5 types: A. cv2.THRESH_BINARY B. cv2.THRESH_BINARY_INV C. cv2.THRESH_TEUNC D. cv2.THRESH_TOZERO E. cv2.THRESH_TOZERO_INV

1.Binary thresholding If the pixel intensity is greater then the set threshold, the value set to 255, otherwise set to 0(black) EQUATION: dst(x,y)={max val(if src(x,y)>thresh), 0(otherwise)}
2.Inverted binary thresholding oppoaite of Binary thresholding

3.Truncated thresholding If the pixel intensity value is greater then threshold ot is truncated to the threshold, thet means the pixel value are set to be the same as threshold and all other values remain same. EQUATION dst(x,y)={threshold(if src(x,y)>thresh), src(x,y)(otherwise)}

4.TOZERO Thresholding The pixel intensity is set to zero, for all the pixel intensity, less than the threshols value. EQUATION: dst(x,y)={src(x,y)(if src(x,y)>thresh), 0(otherwise)}

5.TOZERO INVERTED Thresholding Oppoaite to TO zero EQUATION: dst(x,y)={0(if src(x,y)>thresh), src(x,y)(otherwise)}

1. simple Thresholding/ Global thresholding¶

SYNTAX: -cv2.threshold(src, thresh, maxval, type)

1.cv2.THRESH_BINARY 2.cv2.THRESH_BINARY_INV 3.cv2.Thresh_trunic 3.cv2.THRESH_TOZERO 4.cv2.THRESH_TOZERO_INV

2.otsu's Thresholding(Aug 2023)¶

Otsu's method, named after Nobuyuki Otsu is used to perform automatic image thresholding. In the simplest form, the algorithm returns a single intensity threshold that separate pixels into two classes, foreground and background

Otsu’s Thresholding Concept :

Automatic global thresholding algorithms usually have following steps.

1.Process the input image

2.Obtain image histogram (distribution of pixels)

3.Compute the threshold value T

4.Replace image pixels into white in those regions, where saturation is greater than T and into the black in the opposite cases.

In [ ]:
import cv2 as cv
import numpy as np
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt

img=cv.imread("C:\\Users\\91938\\OneDrive\\Desktop\\chandrayaan\\moon1.jpeg",0)

ADAPTIVE THRESHOLDING(Aug 2023)¶

If an image has different lighting condition in different areas, adaptive thresholding can help. In addition to the parameters describe above, the method cv.adaptiveThresholding takes three inut parameters. In OpenCV, you can perform adaptive thresholding operation on an image using the method adaptiveThresholding() of the Imgproc class. Following is the syntax of this method. adaptiveThreshold(src,dst,maxValue,adaptiveMethod,thresholdType,blockSize, C)This method accepts the following parameters: src-An object of the class Mat representing the source (input)Image dst-An object of the class Mat representing the destination (output)Image maxValue- A variable of double type representing the value that is to be given if pixel value is more than the threshold value. adaptivemethod-A variable of integer the type representing the adaptive method to be used.This will be either of the following two values. ADAPTIVE_THRESH_MEAN_C: -Thresh value is the mean of neighborhood area ADAPTIVE_THRESH_GUASSIAN_C-Threshold values is the weighted sum of neighborhood values where weights are a daussian window. ThresholdType: -A variable of integer type representing the type of threshold to be used. blockSize: - A variable of the integer type representing size of the pixelneighborhood used to calculate the threshold value. c: -A variable of double type representing the constant in the both the method (subtracted from the mean or weighted mean). cv.adaptiveThresholding() is used for adaptiveThresholding

What is Flag Vlaue ?¶

In computer programming, a sentinel value (also referred to as a flag value, trip value, rogue value, signal value, or dummy data) is a special value in the context of an algorithm which uses its presence as a condition of termination, typically in a loop or recursive algorithm. 1.cv2.KMEANS_RANDOM_CENTERS : With this flag enabled, the method always starts with a ramdom state of initial samples ans tries to converge from their depending upon term criteria. 2.cv2.KMEANS_PP_CENTERS : With this flag enabled, the method first iterates the whole image to determine the probaly center then starts to convert. 3.cv2.KMEANS_USE_INITIAL_LABELS : Using this flag we can pass the custom sample which are used by the method to convert.

import cv2
# read the image 
img1=cv2.imread("C:\\Users\\91938\\OneDrive\\Desktop\\chandrayaan\\moon1.jpeg")
img2=cv2.imread("C:\\Users\\91938\\OneDrive\\Desktop\\chandrayaan\\moon2.jpeg")
# convert image to grayscale
img1= cv2.cvtColor(img1,cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
img2= cv2.cvtColor(img2,cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
# create sift object
orb = cv2.ORB_create(nfeatures=500)
# detect features from the image
keypoints1,descriptors1=orb.detectAndCompute(img1,None)
keypoints2,descriptors2=orb.detectAndCompute(img2,None)
# create feature matcher
bf=cv2.BFMatcher(cv2.NORM_L1, crossCheck=True)
# match descriptor of both images
matches= bf.match(descriptors1,descriptors2)
# sort matches by distance
matches=sorted(matches,key=lambda x:x.distance)
# draw first 50 matches
matched_img=cv2.drawMatches(img1,keypoints1,img2,keypoints2,matches[:50],img2,flags=2)
cv2.imshow('image',matched_img)
#save the image
cv2.imwrite("matched_img.jpg",matched_img)
cv2.waitKey(0)
cv2.destroyAllWindows()

ORB¶

ORB is a fusion of FAST keypoint detector and BRIEF descriptor with some added features to improve the performance. FAST is Features from Accelerated Segment Test used to detect features from the provided image. It also uses a pyramid to produce multiscale-features. cv2.BFMatcher=Brute-Force matcher is simple. It takes the descriptor of one feature in first set and is matched with all other features in second set using some distance calculation. And the closest one is returned.

In [ ]:
# ORB
import cv2
img=cv2.imread("C:\\Users\\91938\\OneDrive\\Desktop\\chandrayaan\\moon1.jpeg")
img2=cv2.imread("C:\\Users\\91938\\OneDrive\\Desktop\\chandrayaan\\moon2.jpeg")
img=cv2.cvtColor(img,cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
img2=cv2.cvtColor(img2,cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
orb=cv2.ORB_create()
keypoints_1, descriptors_1 = orb.detectAndCompute(img, None)
keypoints_2, descriptors_2 = orb.detectAndCompute(img2, None)
bf=cv2.BFMatcher (cv2.NORM_L1, crossCheck=True)
matches=bf.match(descriptors_1, descriptors_2)
matches = sorted (matches, key = lambda x:x.distance)
matched_img = cv2.drawMatches (img, keypoints_1, img2, keypoints_2, matches[:30],img2,flags=6)
cv2.imshow('image', matched_img)
cv2.imwrite("matched_images.jpg", matched_img) 
cv2.waitKey (0) 
cv2.destroyAllWindows()

Star¶

STAR is a feature detector derived from CenSurE. Unlike CenSurE however, which uses polygons like squares, hexagons and octagons to approach a circle, Star emulates a circle with 2 overlapping squares: 1 upright and 1 45-degree rotated. These polygons are bi-level.
